SAFE COORDINATOR ROLE DESCRIPTION
The SAFE Coordinator is responsible for overseeing the implementation of aspects
of the churchs ChurchSafe Policy as specified in this role description.
The board commits to train, resource and support the SAFE Coordinator to fulfil
this role description.
PRIMARY RESPONSIBILITIES
Ensuring that the following happens:
Running Safe training at least annually.
Assessing and managing general safety risks (e.g., risks associated with sites used
by the church) and ensuring readiness to activate any resulting emergency
response procedures.
Managing WWCCs and Police Clearances.
Keeping records of safety concerns and incidents.
External reporting.
Reporting to the Board quarterly.
Annually assessing church safety.
ACTIVITIES TO CHAMPION
Development of, and compliance with Code(s) of Conduct.
Compliance with, and development of mechanisms for accountability and support,
including reporting, on the ground supervision, and supervisory meetings.
Active communication of our safety policies to stakeholders.
Ensuring that grounds for reporting and ways to report are known by all
stakeholders.
Cultivation of awareness of the diverse needs of the Vulnerable.
Provision of reasonable support for the Vulnerable to participate in the life of The
Church.
Page 2 of 2
The building of relationships with guardians and carers, and seeking their feedback
on church activities.
Inviting representatives of The Vulnerable to, on certain occasions, participate in
decision making about policy and procedures.
Review of ChurchSafe policy every two years.
ACTIVITIES TO SUPPORT OTHERS IN
Screening, interviewing, and inducting leaders and volunteers.
Internal reporting.
Ensuring information that is collected is handled appropriately.
Fostering a culture where all are treated with dignity and respect.
Keeping community members, especially the vulnerable, informed about their
rights and responsibilities.
Helping the vulnerable to make and maintain healthy relationships with those in
and outside of The Church.
Assessing and managing specific risks (e.g. risks associated with people, programs,
and activities) and ensuring readiness to activate any resulting emergency response
procedures.
